<PubmedArticleSet>
<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">32500280</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2021</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>19</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2021</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1439-6327</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>120</Volume><Issue>8</Issue><PubDate><Year>2020</Year><Month>Aug</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>European journal of applied physiology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Eur J Appl Physiol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Resistance training upregulates skeletal muscle Na<sup>+</sup>, K<sup>+</sup>-ATPase content, with elevations in both &#x3b1;<sub>1</sub> and &#x3b1;<sub>2</sub>, but not &#x3b2; isoforms.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1777</StartPage><EndPage>1785</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1777-1785</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1007/s00421-020-04408-3</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">The Na<sup>+</sup>, K<sup>+</sup>-ATPase (NKA) is important in regulating trans-membrane ion gradients, cellular excitability and muscle function. We investigated the effects of resistance training in healthy young adults on the adaptability of NKA content and of the specific &#x3b1; and &#x3b2; isoforms in human skeletal muscle.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Twenty-one healthy young males (22.9&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;4.6 year; 1.80&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;0.70 m, 85.1&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;17.8 kg, mean&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;SD) underwent 7 weeks of resistance training, training three times per week (RT, n&#x2009;=&#x2009;16) or control (CON, n&#x2009;=&#x2009;5). The training program was effective with a 39% gain in leg press muscle strength (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.001). A resting vastus lateralis muscle biopsy was taken before and following RT or CON and assayed for NKA content ([<sup>3</sup>H]ouabain binding site content) and NKA isoform (&#x3b1;<sub>1</sub>, &#x3b1;<sub>2</sub>, &#x3b2;<sub>1,</sub> &#x3b2;<sub>2</sub>) abundances.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">After RT, each of NKA content (12%, 311&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;76 vs 349&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;76 pmol g wet weight<sup>-1</sup>, p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.01), NKA &#x3b1;<sub>1</sub> (32%, p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.01) and &#x3b1;<sub>2</sub> (10%, p&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.01) isoforms were increased, whereas &#x3b2;<sub>1</sub> (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.18) and &#x3b2;<sub>2</sub> (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.22) isoforms were unchanged. NKA content and isoform abundances were unchanged during CON.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Resistance training increased muscle NKA content through upregulation of both &#x3b1;<sub>1</sub> and &#x3b1;<sub>2</sub> isoforms, which were independent of &#x3b2; isoform changes. In animal models, modulations in &#x3b1;<sub>1</sub> and &#x3b1;<sub>2</sub> isoform abundances in skeletal muscle may affect fatigue resistance during exercise, muscle hypertrophy and strength. Whether similar in-vivo functional benefits of these NKA isoform adaptations occurs in human muscle with resistance training remains to be determined.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Altarawneh</LastName><ForeName>Muath M</ForeName><Initials>MM</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-2354-4951</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Petersen</LastName><ForeName>Aaron C</ForeName><Initials>AC</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-1508-748X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Farr</LastName><ForeName>Trevor</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Garnham</LastName><ForeName>Andrew</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Broatch</LastName><ForeName>James R</ForeName><Initials>JR</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-0082-3168</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Physiology, Australian Institute of Sport (AIS), Canberra, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Halson</LastName><ForeName>Shona</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1047-3878</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Physiology, Australian Institute of Sport (AIS), Canberra, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Behavioural and Health Sciences, Australian Catholic University, Brisbane, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bishop</LastName><ForeName>David J</ForeName><Initials>DJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-6956-9188</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute for Health and Sport (iHeS), Victoria University, PO Box 14428, Melbourne, VIC, 8001, Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McKenna</LastName><ForeName>Michael J</ForeName><Initials>MJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-